    {
      "id": "f828db0f2c109b51baba552e9e6f68dffe801053",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-22 02:22:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n(3 inline comments)\n\nPatch is pretty good.\n\nOne improvement I was thinking about is to make it impossible to modify the OSD in DRY_RUN mode. With e2fsck in dry-run mode the device is opened read-only and if any code is not checking for dry-run mode before trying to fix some problem it will generate an error. I was wondering if it was possible to set some flag in the LFSCK env that will return an error if there are any calls to declare transactions or similar.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a329386078a9ae9570a7bdf7e8ebba1386899f90",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-09-22 03:27:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (3 inline comments)\n\nBecause the OSD device is not mounted as readonly, and our OI scrub is an online tool. It is not easy to find an unique place to control the system modification without depending on the callers' checking. We needs to know whether the modification is from OI scrub or for normal RPC handling, that needs some additional parameter(s) from the callers, if some OI scrub code forgot or give wrong parameter(s), then related control will be failed. Such additional work is not cheaper than checking \"dryrun\" mode by OI scrub itself.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a1b1b7fd1fef86efb1f03c36bb323b0988052030",
      "author": {
